The top level of a Dart program is a group of definitions, like in Java or C#, instead of a series of imperative statements. That makes it easier for static analysis, since you don&#x27;t have strange constructs like:<p><pre><code>    if (itsTuesday) {
      class Foo {
        ...
      }
    }
</code></pre>
It also means mutual recursion just works, without weird semantic shenanigans like hoisting in JavaScript. In Dart, the top-level is &quot;simultaneous&quot;: all of those definitions are <i>static</i> with no mixing of side-effecting imperative code at the top-level which would make ordering matter.<p>The main side-effect of this approach is that you have to wrap your entrypoint imperative code in a main() function. It&#x27;s a pretty small price to pay, especially in an application with thousands of lines of code.
